data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **4 patterns** that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| Cancellable work loop | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| Thread.ResetAbort | Prevents rethrow to keep loop alive | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check to decide whether to continue |
| Blocking call interruption | `GetNextItem()` may block | Pass token to blocking call; use `token.WaitHandle` |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it will never actually stop your thread. `Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws. Your `Stop()` method becomes a no-op after the 2-second wait.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. The while-loop condition will
                // exit naturally since token.IsCancellationRequested is true.
                // If you wanted to continue processing (like ResetAbort did),
                // you would use a per-item CancellationTokenSource instead.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null || _workerThread == null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation (replaces _running = false AND Thread.Abort)

        // Wait for the thread to finish. No need for Thread.Abort —
        // the token unblocks GetNextItem and exits the loop.
        _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### What must change in `GetNextItem`

This is the **critical pitfall** — if `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), cancellation won't take effect until it unblocks. You must thread the token through:

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — Thread.Abort would forcibly interrupt this
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely
}

// AFTER (.NET 8) — cooperative: checks the token
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}

// If using Thread.Sleep while waiting:
// BEFORE:
Thread.Sleep(1000);
// AFTER:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000); // returns early if token is cancelled
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | What happens | Fix |
|---------|-------------|-----|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | `Stop()` signals cancel but thread stays blocked forever | Pass `CancellationToken` to every blocking call |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Caller never knows cancellation happened | Only catch at the top-level loop; let it propagate elsewhere |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Timer and callback leaks | Implement `IDisposable`, dispose in `Stop()` or `Dispose()` |
| **Expecting immediate stop** | Cancellation only works at checkpoints | Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations inside `ProcessItem` |
| **Using `Thread.Interrupt` as a fallback** | Also obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) | Use `CancellationToken` exclusively |

### If you need per-item cancellation (matching ResetAbort behavior)

Your original `ResetAbort` allowed the loop to continue after aborting one item. To replicate this — cancel one item but keep processing:

```csharp
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    // Per-item CTS, linked to the parent so global stop still works
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
    try
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(token);
        ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Only the item was cancelled, not the whole processor — continue loop
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    }
    finally
    {
        FlushBuffers();
    }
}
```

This gives external code a handle (`itemCts`) to cancel a single item without stopping the entire processor — the cooperative equivalent of `ResetAbort`.
